    preview: "It is a disturbing absurdity that the law meant to protect our children online was written in 1998—an era before smartphones, social media, and the constant harvesting of their digital lives. As the F",
    messageBody: "It is a disturbing absurdity that the law meant to protect our children online was written in 1998—an era before smartphones, social media, and the constant harvesting of their digital lives. As the FTC recently acknowledged, there has been an 'explosion' in internet-connected technology since COPPA was enacted nearly thirty years ago [1]. Today, COPPA is literally older than the children it is supposed to protect.\n\n[Personal Connection]\n\nWe are currently witnessing the consequences of this frozen-in-time policy. Just last month, legal analysis highlighted how 'kidfluencers' are being pushed to produce hundreds of videos, sometimes working twelve hours a day, seven days a week, with zero compensation and no privacy [2]. Because our frameworks haven't kept pace, we are allowing a new generation of digital exploitation to flourish under the guise of 'content creation.'\n\nThis isn't just about screen time; it is about the mass collection of 'personally identifiable sensitive data,' including geolocation and biometric information, by entities that view our children as data mines rather than people [3]. While the FTC has begun looking into age-verification technologies to bridge this gap [4], the pace of regulation is still losing to the pace of extraction.\n\nI am asking you to move beyond 'reminders' and policy statements. We need aggressive enforcement of existing labor and privacy codes against those exploiting minors for profit, and a modernized federal standard that recognizes the digital realities of 2026. Our children should not be forced to rely on 20th-century protections for 21st-century violations.\n\n[Name]",
