    preview: "It is heartbreaking to watch our state choose the most expensive way to fail families. When we send someone to prison for a drug-related offense, we aren’t just spending taxpayer dollars; we are payin",
    messageBody: "It is heartbreaking to watch our state choose the most expensive way to fail families. When we send someone to prison for a drug-related offense, we aren’t just spending taxpayer dollars; we are paying a premium to ensure a family is broken and a cycle of recidivism continues, even when a cheaper, more effective path is right in front of us.\n\n[Personal Connection]\n\nThe fiscal reality is staggering. In Oregon, it costs approximately $184 per day—$67,273 a year—to incarcerate one person [1]. By contrast, the Family Sentencing Alternative Program (FSAP) operates at just $27 per day, or $9,855 annually [1]. We are choosing to spend nearly seven times more money for a process that often yields worse outcomes. Even new digital recovery ecosystems supported by courts can deliver results for as little as $1,800 per year, compared to the $36,500 to $73,000 we waste on a single year of jail time [2].\n\nEven those who prioritize traditional law enforcement and 'stopping crime' acknowledge that the 'poison of fentanyl and addiction' must be confronted directly [4]. The federal government is already moving to provide resources to combat this crisis [3], but Oregon must decide how to use its own power. We cannot afford—morally or financially—to keep choosing incarceration over the treatment courts that actually keep our neighbors stable and our families together.\n\nI am asking you to prioritize and expand funding for drug treatment courts and alternative sentencing programs like FSAP in the current budget. Please choose the investment that saves both money and lives.\n\n[Name]",
